{"pattern":{"summary":"Redundant boolean combination of two monotonic ordered floating-point comparisons against different constants on the same SSA value.","match_conditions":["A boolean `and` or `or` combines two `fcmp` instructions.","Both `fcmp`s use the same ordered monotonic predicate class: either both `olt`/`ole`-like lower-than comparisons or both `ogt`/`oge`-like greater-than comparisons. The exact motivating example is `olt`, but the reusable fold should cover monotonic ordered same-direction predicates where implication is determined solely by constant ordering.","Both `fcmp`s compare the same floating-point SSA value against two constant FP operands.","The compared SSA value must be the same operand after accounting for commuted forms where legal.","The constants must be comparable by APFloat ordering in the same semantics.","Fast-math flags such as `nsz` may be present and should be preserved on the surviving compare when sound."],"rewrite_rules":["For `or`: replace the boolean combine with the less restrictive comparison, because the stronger comparison implies the weaker one.","For ordered less-than predicates (`olt` / similarly `ole`): `fcmp x < C1 or fcmp x < C2` simplifies to `fcmp x < max(C1,C2)`; `fcmp x <= C1 or fcmp x <= C2` simplifies to `fcmp x <= max(C1,C2)`.","For ordered greater-than predicates (`ogt` / similarly `oge`): `fcmp x > C1 or fcmp x > C2` simplifies to `fcmp x > min(C1,C2)`; `fcmp x >= C1 or fcmp x >= C2` simplifies to `fcmp x >= min(C1,C2)`.","For `and`: replace the boolean combine with the more restrictive comparison.","For ordered less-than predicates (`olt` / similarly `ole`): `fcmp x < C1 and fcmp x < C2` simplifies to `fcmp x < min(C1,C2)`; `fcmp x <= C1 and fcmp x <= C2` simplifies to `fcmp x <= min(C1,C2)`.","For ordered greater-than predicates (`ogt` / similarly `oge`): `fcmp x > C1 and fcmp x > C2` simplifies to `fcmp x > max(C1,C2)`; `fcmp x >= C1 and fcmp x >= C2` simplifies to `fcmp x >= max(C1,C2)`."],"notes":["This is implication-based folding: one compare subsumes the other because the threshold is weaker/stronger under the same monotonic predicate.","Ordered predicates are important because NaN behavior must remain identical; with two ordered comparisons on the same operand, NaN yields false for both and does not invalidate implication.","Equivalent boolean forms expressed via `select i1 %a, i1 true, i1 %b` (OR) or `select i1 %a, i1 %b, i1 false` (AND) should also simplify the same way.","The motivating bug was specifically `or` of two `fcmp nsz olt` on the same loaded double with different constants."],"implementation_hint":"This naturally fits `simplifyAndOrOfFCmps()` / InstSimplify-style logic: match same-direction ordered `fcmp`s on the same non-constant operand with constant FP RHSs, compare constants via APFloat, then select the surviving compare according to boolean op and predicate direction."},"testcases":[{"name":"or_olt_double_basic_larger_bound_survives","ir":"define i1 @or_olt_double_basic_larger_bound_survives(ptr %arg0) {
